ype="pubmed">21346038</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Understanding the impact of Belzutifan on treatment strategies for patients with VHL. Arevalo A, Patel N, Muraki P, et al. J Kidney Cancer VHL. 2022;9:41&#x2013;46.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC9551368</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">36310638</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Hypoxia inducible factor-2&#x3b1; (HIF-2&#x3b1;) pathway inhibitors. Dogra R, Vaishampayan U. J Kidney Cancer VHL. 2025;12:1&#x2013;15.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC12228116</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">40620865</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>A Phase I dose-escalation study of the HIF-2 alpha inhibitor DFF332 in patients with advanced clear-cell renal cell carcinoma. Pal SK, Bernard-Tessier A, Grell P, et al. Clin Cancer Res. 2025;31:1847&#x2013;1855.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC12079095</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">40043000</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>HIF-2 complex dissociation, target inhibition, and acquired resistance with PT2385, a first-in-class HIF-2 inhibitor, in patients with clear cell renal cell carcinoma. Courtney KD, Ma Y, Diaz de Leon A, et al. Clin Cancer Res. 2020;26:793&#x2013;803.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC7024660</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">31727677</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">42050152</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>24</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>24</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1759-4782</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>23</Volume><Issue>7</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Jul</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Nature reviews. Clinical oncology</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Nat Rev Clin Oncol</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>The clinical landscape of HIF2&#x3b1; inhibitors in oncology.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>501</StartPage><EndPage>519</EndPage><MedlinePgn>501-519</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1038/s41571-026-01145-y</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Hypoxia-inducible factor 2&#x3b1; (HIF2&#x3b1;; also known as endothelial PAS domain-containing protein 1) had long been considered an undruggable transcription factor until the discovery of an allosteric pocket within its PAS-B domain enabled the development of selective small-molecule antagonists. Belzutifan, the first-in-class HIF2&#x3b1; inhibitor, has since demonstrated substantial efficacy in patients with von Hippel-Lindau (VHL) disease-associated tumours, sporadic clear-cell renal cell carcinoma (ccRCC), and pheochromocytoma or paraganglioma, thereby validating HIF2&#x3b1; as a therapeutic target in patients with cancer. In this Review, we summarize the biology of the VHL-HIF signalling pathway, the structural basis for HIF2&#x3b1; druggability and the clinical milestones leading to the multiple regulatory approvals of belzutifan. We also highlight emerging data on other small-molecule inhibitors, RNA interference approaches and indirect modulators that have the potential to expand the scope of HIF pathway suppression. Combination strategies offer opportunities to enhance efficacy and overcome resistance; however, key challenges remain, including the identification of predictive biomarkers, mechanisms of primary and acquired resistance, and optimal management approaches for on-target toxicities such as anaemia and hypoxia. Finally, we discuss the increasing potential of HIF2&#x3b1; inhibition beyond kidney cancer, including its role in hypoxia-adapted malignancies, and outline priorities for future translational and clinical research.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; 2026. Springer Nature Limited.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y" EqualContrib="Y"><LastName>Saad</LastName><ForeName>Eddy</ForeName><Initials>E</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0001-8700-9312</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, Boston, MA, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medicine, Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, Boston, MA, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Harvard Medical School, Boston, MA, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y" EqualContrib="Y"><LastName>Machaalani</LastName><ForeName>Marc</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-6708-9922</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, Boston, MA, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Harvard Medical School, Boston, MA, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>McDermott</LastName><ForeName>David F</ForeName><Initials>DF</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-2675-5095</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, Boston, MA, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Harvard Medical School, Boston, MA, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of Medical Oncology, Department of Medicine, Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, Boston, MA, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Choueiri</LastName><ForeName>Toni K</ForeName><Initials>TK</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-9201-3217</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, Boston, MA, USA. toni_chouei